          "body": "Peter closes (2:22) by quoting two proverbs — one from Proverbs 26:11, one from extra-biblical wisdom — to make the same point twice: outward cleansing without nature-change yields return to filth. The *dog* and the *sow* are unclean animals by Jewish reckoning; even when they appear cleansed, they revert to their nature. This is Peter's final diagnostic for the false teachers and those who follow them. The chapter's last image is not the day of judgment but the dog at its own vomit — a deliberately revolting picture meant to inoculate the reader against the seductive freedom the teachers were preaching. Nature, not behavior, is the decisive issue. The new birth (1:4, 'partakers of the divine nature') is what the false teachers lack, and chapter 2 is the photographic negative of chapter 1."
